##South Korea complains about Israel's "over-vaccination" , Israel pays for a charter flight to send 400 South Koreans home

Due to the increasing number of newly diagnosed cases of pneumonia in Korea, 16 countries have taken measures to restrict entry into Korea or strengthen quarantine measures. Among them, Israel and other countries "over-reaction" triggered the South Korean side of strong dissatisfaction.

As of 9:00 am on February 25, there were 60 newly confirmed cases of coronary pneumonia in South Korea, bringing the total to 893. According to Yonhap on the 24th, North Gyeongsang Province's 39 Catholics during February 8 to 16 pilgrimage to Israel, of which 18 in 21 to 22 were diagnosed with new crown pneumonia, another 12 in 24 confirmed a total of 30 people.

The News, along with a sharp rise in confirmed cases in South Korea over the past few days, immediately caused panic in Israel. On the 22nd, Israel banned all flights from Japan and South Korea. Nearly 200 passengers from South Korea and other countries were denied entry into Israeli territory on a Korean Air Korean Airlines flight KE957 after it landed at Ben Gurion airport in Israel, and 12 Israeli passengers on board were sent straight home for 14 days.

In addition, the Israeli side also told about 1,000 South Korean tourists currently traveling in Israel: Avoid entering public places, consciously isolated in hotels, waiting for the relevant departments to take appropriate measures.

On the 23rd, South Korea's foreign ministry expressed regret over Israel's decision to deny entry to South Koreans. After consultations between the two countries, the Israeli government arranged two chartered flights on the 24th to send back some 400 South Korean citizens who had been refused entry, all expenses being borne by Israel. The South Korean Foreign Ministry said it would continue to arrange follow-up flights to help South Korean tourists return to South Korea.

South Korea's East Asia daily said on the 24th that suspicion of South Korea is spreading rapidly in Israel, where not only have demonstrations against South Korea taken place, but also a number of hotels and restaurants have posted signs forbidding South Koreans to enter, this has made it more difficult for South Korean tourists stranded in Israel to get food, clothing and shelter.

In addition to Israel, the Republic of Mauritius has recently adopted immigration control measures against Koreans. South Korean Foreign Ministry officials say the government has suspended the entry of South Koreans arriving in Mauritius because of fever and other symptoms. South Korean media said that this includes 17 South Korean couples who just got married.

South Korean Foreign Minister Kang kyung-wha said in an interview at the United Nations Office in Geneva on the 24th that the Israeli government has taken excessive measures, restricting entry and expelling those who have entered the country are measures of different levels, south Korea is maintaining close communication with the local government through its diplomatic missions abroad.

As of the 24th, seven countries, including Israel, Bahrain and Jordan, have banned the entry of foreigners from South Korea. Nine other countries, including Brunei, Britain and Kazakhstan, force South Korean tourists to undergo medical examinations in isolation facilities. The US raised the level of its travel advice from "normal precautions" to "more prudent" .

South Korea's "joongang daily" editorial published on the 25th, said that foreign governments want to ensure the safety of their own people to take certain measures, but the implementation of a ban on entry is another matter, they must protect the human rights of South Korean tourists. The Israeli and Mauritian initiatives are very disappointing in this regard. "We can not force other countries to end their travel bans, but our governments must do their utmost to reduce such unjustified discrimination. "

"If our government had been in close communication with the Israeli government, such a setback could have been avoided, " the article said, "The loss of international credibility will allow anti-korean sentiment to directly affect the vitality of the South Korean economy and discourage cross-border travel by business people, which may lead to foreign antipathy towards South Korean products. "
